    <stitle>T 444E Diesel Engine Diagnostics (NAVPAK) (1997) - SECTION 1.6: SENSOR OPERATION - TYPES OF SENSORS</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>TYPES OF SENSORS</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="PROCTYPE" graphiccount="1">
            <title>THERMISTOR</title>
            <para>A thermistor is a type of sensor which changes it's electrical resistance with temperature that its
                being exposed to. The electrical resistance of the thermistor decreases as temperature increases and
                increases as temperature decreases. The sensor in conjunction with a current limiting resistor in the
                ECM
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1900602">1.23</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                forms a voltage divider network that provides a voltage signal which will be matched with a particular
                temperature value.
            </para>
            <para>The top half of the voltage divider is the current limiting resistor internal to the ECM. A thermistor
                sensor has two electrical connections, signal return and ground. The output of a thermistor sensor is a
                non linear analog signal.
            </para>
            <para>Examples:</para>
            <para>EOT Engine Oil Temperature</para>
            <para>ECT Engine Coolant Temperature Sensor</para>
            <para>IAT Intake Temperature Sensor</para>
            <figure id="f1900602" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg1108" filename="../figeg1/EG1108.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 1.23 Thermistor Engine Coolant Temperature (ECT)</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
